This proof works by first establishing the equivalence between `x = y` and `x.beq y = true` using the `Iff.intro` tactic. The forward direction (`x = y ⇒ x.beq y = true`) is straightforward: if `x = y`, then all their bits are equal, so `beq` will return `true`. The backward direction (`x.beq y = true ⇒ x = y`) is more involved and requires showing that if all corresponding bits of `x` and `y` are equal, then the vectors are equal. 

The proof uses `Classical.em` to split into cases `x = y` and `x ≠ y`, and then uses the established equivalence to simplify the goal in each case. The `simp_all` tactic is used to handle the simplifications, and `induction` is used to handle the recursive structure of `beq` (though in this case, it seems the `simp_all` approach suffices without needing explicit induction due to the way the goal is set up).

